nuclei in the nucleon resonance region.

x4freetext: ADONE storage ring.
Cylindrical NaI crystal annulus (32 cm
long, 15 cm thick, and 5 cm of internal diameter0 as
a hadron detector. A dense SF-6 lead-glass cylinder,
30 cm long and 12 cm in diameter as an
electromagnetic shower detector.
Photohadronic technique which provided a direct and
absolute determination of the photoabsorpion cross
section by measuring the production rate of hadronic
events, and rejecting the preponderant electromagnetic
events mainly by an angular separation. In fact,
while the hadronic events are more largely
distributed in angle, the electromagnetic event
distribution is strongly peaked in the forward
direction and therefore can be suppressed by using
a high efficiency electromagnetic shower detector
as a veto counter.
Statistical errors only.
uncertainty in the photon beam flux
uncertainty in the target thickness
uncertainties in the calibration and
threshold efficiency of both the shower and hadron
detectors (above 600 MeV this contribution is
constant with energy and increases from 2% to 6.5%
with the target mass number A, while, in the
delta-resonance region, where it depends both on
energy and A, it varies from 4.5% to 7.5%.
(All Systematic uncertainties are given as
error bars on fig. 6.)
The total photoabsorption cross sections for 7Li, C,
Al, Cu, Sn, and Pb have been measured in the energy
range 300 - 1200 MeV at Frascati with the jet-target
tagged photon beam. A 4pi NaI crystal detector and a
lead-glass shower counter were used, respectively, to
measure hadronic events and to reject the
electromagnetic background. Data above 600 MeV
clearly indicate a broadening of higher nucleon
resonance peaks in nuclei and a reduction of the
absolute value of the cross section per nucleon
with the respect to free-nucleon case.
This large broadening suggests a strong influence of
the nuclear medium in the resonance propagation and
interaction, while the systematic reduction of the
measured cross sections might Be due to a depletion
of the resonance excitation strength and to the onset
of the shadowing effect around 1 GeV. Moreover,
systematic study carried out indicates that also the
delta-resonance excitation parameters are not the
same for all nuclei, being its mass and width
increasing with the nuclear density.
Data were compiled at the USA BNL NNDC by
V.V.Varlamov.
